## Executive Summary

Sweden, via Sida, is a top-tier humanitarian donor providing substantial
but variably timed funding, totaling \$130.8 million in 2025 with a
strong regional focus on East Africa. Its geographic reach is expanding
rapidly, now supporting 18 countries, emphasizing a strategic
diversification. Sida’s higher-than-average earmarking (around 25%-39%)
reflects a preference for targeted, outcome-driven investments. Funding
patterns reveal spikes aligned with emerging needs, though overall
disbursements are less frequent and smaller compared to other major
donors, indicating potential challenges in responsiveness and
flexibility. Fundraisers should align proposals with Sida’s priority
regions, especially East Africa, emphasize clear, defined objectives,
and advocate for more predictable, scaled financing.

## Earmarking

The bar chart displays Sweden’s 2025 international development funding

presented. The highest funding allocation is directed to East Africa
with a maximum value reaching 73.6 million USD, significantly outpacing

priority East Africa holds in Swedish development cooperation for 2025.
Other regions receive comparatively lower, yet meaningful, support.
These funding patterns highlight potential opportunities to align new
proposals with East African needs while considering underfunded regions

## Comparison

This bar chart compares the earmarking profiles of the Swedish
International Development Cooperation Agency (Sida) against the average
of other donors across all years. Sida’s total funding amounts to
approximately 4.96 billion USD, with an average earmarked share of 25%.
This share is notably higher than the average earmarking level among
other donors, which hovers around 15% to 18%, indicating Sida
prioritizes allocating funds to specific targets. The distribution of
funding shows Sida’s earmarked funding proportion peaks near 39%,
contrasting with a lower and more varied range seen in other donors.
This pattern reflects Sida’s strategic focus on designated funding which
can be leveraged to advocate for more predictable, targeted investments.
Humanitarian proposal writers should consider this earmarking tendency
when designing projects or seeking Sida funding, emphasizing clearly
defined, outcome-oriented activities aligned with Sida’s priority areas
to maximize funding potential.

The alluvial chart presents Sida’s funding disbursements to seven

distribution suggests changes in priority or needs assessments across
regions, with some country groups receiving increased shares and others
decreasing. For humanitarian proposal planning, this trend highlights
the importance of monitoring evolving donor preferences and aligning
project designs to match shifting funding landscapes. Given the
concentration of funds in certain groups and variability over time,

focus for 2022-2025 may increase funding success chances. Closer
attention should be paid to the country groups experiencing the largest

## Diversification

This line chart tracks the number of recipient countries benefiting from

countries over time, outpacing many other donors. For proposal writers,

## Volatility

This visualization depicts the funding volatility of Sweden’s
contributions through Sida over multiple transaction dates, with 76
transactions recorded. On average, Sida transactions have an amount of
1.4 million USD with approximately 25.3 transactions per year. This
contrasts markedly with the top 10 donors who have nearly double the
average transaction amount at 2.9 million USD and a substantially higher
transaction frequency at 371.3 per year. The data indicates that Sida’s
funding is less frequent and smaller in size compared to major donors,
which suggests potential limitations in flexibility and responsiveness
when allocating funds. Such volatility and lower volume might affect the
ability to scale programs quickly in response to humanitarian needs. For
proposal writers and fundraisers, these insights highlight the
opportunity to advocate for increased and more stable financing from
Sida. Aligning funding requests with Sida’s transaction patterns and
times can enhance fund securing success. Furthermore, emphasizing the
comparative difference in transaction frequency and size in proposals
can underscore the need for more consistent and larger contributions to
improve program reach and impact. Monitoring these funding trends is
crucial for strategic planning and ensuring operational continuity.
